  "slug": "pork-pie",
  "title": "Pork Pie",
  "subtitle": "A hand-raised hot water crust filled with seasoned pork mince and jelly",
  "excerpt": "The British pork pie is a cold pie in a rigid hot water crust pastry, filled with seasoned pork and sealed with savoury aspic poured in through a hole in the lid. Melton Mowbray is the most famous type, but the method is accessible at home with a loose-bottomed cake tin.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional British raised pie. Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: raised pork pie method. Clarissa Dickson Wright and Jennifer Paterson, Two Fat Ladies (1996): pork pie with jelly. Melton Mowbray Pork Pie Association standards.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The pork pie is one of the most technically demanding things in the British pastry tradition. The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "hot water crust",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmp879i8x0000ucv4pmfer90b"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " must be worked quickly while warm and pliable, then moulded into a tin before it stiffens. The filling is raw seasoned pork that must reach 75°C throughout.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "aspic jelly",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr3yjk00007kv4uxgcwxsa"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " is poured in after baking through a small hole left in the lid. As the pork cooks, it shrinks and leaves a gap; the jelly fills this and sets cold, giving the characteristic solid texture when sliced.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you need",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
