      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the hot water crust",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sift ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{plain-flour}} of flour",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " into a large bowl and make a well. Heat ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{lard}} of lard",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " with 175 ml of water until the lard has melted and the liquid is just boiling. Pour into the flour well and stir quickly with a wooden spoon until the dough comes together. Tip onto a lightly floured board and knead for 1 minute until smooth. Work quickly: the dough stiffens as it cools.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Line the tin and fill",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Reserve a quarter of the dough for the lid. Press the remaining dough into a lightly greased 900 g loaf tin, pushing it up the sides to an even thickness of about 5 mm. Combine the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{pork-mince}} of pork mince",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sausagemeat}} of sausagemeat",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " with the dried sage, ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{mace}} of mace",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and the filling salt. Pack firmly into the lined tin. Roll the reserved dough for the lid, lay it on top, and seal the edges. Make a 1 cm hole in the centre of the lid. Brush with beaten egg.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake and fill with jelly",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Bake for 20 minutes, then reduce to 180°C (160°C fan) and bake for a further 60-70 minutes. A probe through the steam hole should read 75°C in the filling. Cool in the tin for 30 minutes, then turn out and cool completely. Heat the stock until just simmering (add gelatine powder if the stock is not rich enough to set naturally). Pour slowly through the steam hole; the jelly will fill the gaps as the pie sits. Refrigerate for at least 8 hours before slicing.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Aim for an even 5 mm wall throughout. Pack the filling firmly so it supports the walls from the inside.",
              "cause": "Pastry too thin, or pressed to the tin unevenly",
              "symptom": "Pastry walls collapse inward during baking"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add 2 tsp of powdered gelatine dissolved in 2 tbsp of cold water to the hot stock before pouring. Stir to combine.",
              "cause": "Stock was not rich enough in natural gelatine",
              "symptom": "Jelly does not set"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use pork mince with 20% fat rather than a higher-fat variety. Allow the full 8 hours of refrigeration.",
              "cause": "Too much fat in the filling, or the pie was cut before the jelly fully set",
              "symptom": "Pastry is soggy at the base"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Moisten the dough-to-dough join with a small amount of water and press firmly. Egg wash helps seal lids.",
              "cause": "The join was not sealed thoroughly when assembling",
              "symptom": "The lid separates from the side walls"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The British pork pie is picnic food, pub food, and ploughman's lunch food. Its origins are in the Victorian and Edwardian tradition of portable cold pies made for field workers and market-goers. Melton Mowbray in Leicestershire is the geographical heart of the tradition, with Protected Geographical Indication status. The home version is a worthy approximation.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
